note.p:
    Another way to think about a vector is as a difference between two
  points, or the arrow from one point to another.  For instance, {1\choose 2} is the arrow from (1,1) to (2,3).


\begin{tikzpicture}[whitebg nodes, thin border nodes]
\draw[help lines] (0,0) grid (4,4);
\draw[->] (0,0) -- (4,0);
\draw[->] (0,0) -- (0,4);
\point["${(1,1)}$" {left, text=seq-red}, seq-red] (x) at (1,1);
\point["${(2,3)}$" {right, text=seq-green}, seq-green] (y) at (2,3);
\draw[vector, seq-blue] (x)
  -- node[below right=1pt] {${1\choose 2}$} (y);
\end{tikzpicture}

example.p:
In this example, the two vectors and the point all correspond to the coordinates
    (1,3). The vectors are equal, but one is based while the other is not.


  \begin{tikzpicture}[whitebg nodes, thin border nodes]
